How will the decision of the Central Bank to reduce the key rate affect the economy
The Bank of Russia is expected to reduce the key rate again.
It fell by another 0.25 percentage points, to 4.25% per annum - formally the next historical minimum.
Judging by the return of a short step of rate reduction, as well as the tone of the statements of the Central Bank and updated forecasts for the Russian economy, the regulator looks at the economic prospects more optimistically than before.
This means that the current cycle of monetary easing may soon stop.
“We have continued to ease monetary policy, primarily given that there are still risks of inflation deviation down from 4% in 2021,” said the head of the Bank of Russia Elvira Nabiullina.
They are associated with a significant decline in economic activity, a fall in domestic and external demand.
The economic recovery, according to Nabiullina, will take more than a year and a half.
At the same time, she noted that after the lifting of restrictions due to the pandemic, economic processes were revived: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand were restored, construction and production of consumer goods were expanded, the annual rate of decline in freight turnover of transport and industrial production slowed down.
According to the updated forecast of the Central Bank, in 2020 the contraction of the economy will be 4.5-5.5% (previously expected 4-6%), and the recovery growth of the economy in 2021 will be 3.5-4.5%, in 2022 - 2.5-3.5%.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised its forecast for annual oil prices to $ 38 and $ 40 per barrel Urals in 2020 and 2021, respectively.
Previously, the Central Bank expected 27 and 35 dollars per barrel.
Finally, the Bank of Russia’s inflation forecast for 2020 was 3.7-4.2% against the previously expected 3.8-4.8%.
The Bank of Russia’s view on the situation in the economy is becoming more optimistic, which brings us closer to the end of the cycle of easing, according to economists for Russia and the CIS “Renaissance Capital” Sofia Donets and Andrei Melashchenko.
Thus, the Bank of Russia has consistently reduced the key rate for more than a year, since the beginning of last summer it has fallen by 3.5 percentage points.
And at the last meeting in June, the Central Bank lowered it by one percentage point immediately due to low inflation rates due to depressed demand and the need to stimulate the economy stalled due to the pandemic and related restrictions.
The chances of additional adjustment of monetary policy remain (at the next meeting on September 18 and until the end of the year), but the limit is already close, agrees the chief analyst of Rosbank Evgeny Koshelev.
The combination of pro-inflationary risks also points to a near pause in the easing of interest-rate policy - disrupted supply chains, possible cost increases due to epidemic prevention measures, and a faster (than expected) recovery in demand, he says.
In addition, subsequent actions of the Bank of Russia will require more attention to inflationary processes during the harvest season, as well as external volatility, increased against the background of geopolitical conflicts, Koshelev points out.
One way or another, a reduction in the key rate will lead to a further reduction in rates for the most reliable borrowers, as well as, possibly, on mortgages, says Maxim Petronevich, senior economist at the analytical department of Otkritie Bank.
The correction of rates will be less pronounced than the reduction of the key rate, he said.
Interest rates on consumer loans may fall by another 0.3-0.6 percentage points during the second half of the year, mortgage rates may end the year in the range of 6.2-7%, does not exclude the economist "BKS Premier" Anton Pokatovich.
Average interest rates on deposits, in his opinion, will also fall - in the coming months they may fall to 4.2-4.5% (currently barely above 4.5%).
Next, they may fall to 4% if the Central Bank lowers the key rate in the fall, says Pokatovich.
